2026-04-21 01:32:46 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient light sensor in control (ambient sensor) module', 'relay driver / threshold comparator circuit in control (ambient sensor) module'] hypothesis_explanation='All modules have correct supply polarity and steady DC voltage from the power supply through to the load. The load‑module diode and both lamps behave nominally, and measurements at the load show a solid 11–12 V with no intrinsic fault. The timing potentiometer was verified good by replacement, but when the timing control and the ambient‑light level are exercised, the simulator repeatedly reports a non‑convergent, unstable/oscillating state, while the relay remains closed and the lamp appears steady in that particular test snapshot.\n\nThese observations localize the abnormal behavior to the control module’s sensing/decision circuitry rather than to the supply, cabling, or load. A realistic root cause is that the ambient light sensor or its comparator/driver stage is defective or mis‑biased, placing the relay control loop right at its switching threshold. Small inherent noise or sensor output fluctuations then cause the relay drive node to oscillate, periodically modulating the series path that feeds the lamp and creating the observed 0.5 s dropouts. The power LED stays solid because the battery and its local indicator are not in this feedback path.\n\nThus, the most probable fault is within the ambient‑light sensor and its associated comparator/relay‑driver circuitry in the control module, which together form the unstable, oscillating control loop that intermittently de‑energizes the lamp despite an otherwise healthy system.'
