2026-04-21 01:33:15 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['sensitivity potentiometer on control (ambient sensor) module'] hypothesis_explanation='The intermittent 0.5 s lamp dropout and simulator non‑convergence occur while the power supply, relay, lamp, diode, and inter‑module cabling all test good. Internal measurements show the control module’s bias node oscillating between ~11.85 V and ~5.94 V, while both potentiometers have 11.85 V on one end, ~0.02 V on the other, and their wipers are *electrically disconnected* from the rest of the circuit during diagnostics.\n\nPrevious hypotheses have already ruled out: (1) the timing potentiometer element and its wiper connection (explicitly repaired/replaced without effect) and (2) the ambient‑light sensor and comparator / relay driver circuitry. The only remaining adjustment element that can destabilize the threshold / bias point around which the comparator operates, thereby causing a slow 20 s oscillation and brief loss of drive, is the **sensitivity potentiometer’s setting** itself, not its continuity.\n\nWith both rails correctly present on the sensitivity pot, an extreme or inappropriate wiper position can bias the comparator close to its switching threshold so that normal sensor noise and internal loading periodically push the loop into oscillation, reproducing the observed periodic flicker and the simulator’s report of an unstable state. Correcting (re‑setting) the sensitivity control to the intended operating range would remove the oscillation without changing any other component.\n\nTherefore the most plausible root cause is a mis‑adjusted sensitivity potentiometer on the ambient sensor module (configuration fault rather than hardware damage).'
